The red and blue illusion: The brightness changes based on your distance from the screen because of the density differences of rods and cones in the macula (central retina).  In the very center of our vision (fovea) there only exists cone photoreceptors responsible for detecting color and fine detail and as you move away from the fovea the density of rods increases which are responsible for contrast sensitivity, motion and black/white vision.  So when moving closer to the screen the picture takes up more of our visual field and thus we use more of the rods and they are stimulated to make the picture seem to increase in brightness; conversely while moving away from the screen the picture takes up less of our central visual field decreasing the amount of rod photoreceptors used and increasing the percentage of cones being used making the colors of the image appear bolder. illusion explained.
